@flexiarg t3/implementation-modes
@title Implementation Modes
@sigils [🔀/态]
@audience programme-evaluators, institutional-leads, implementation-researchers
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/transformation-space
@see t3/architectural-pair, t3/com-b-convergence
@next t3/com-b-convergence
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Three implementation modes — multiplied input, absorbed input, and architectural mismatch — are distinguished not by training quality or trainer motivation but by the institutional architecture that receives the training. In multiplied-input mode, existing structures amplify the training into sustained collective practice. In absorbed-input mode, individual goodwill sustains delivery without institutional support, creating fragile dependence. In architectural-mismatch mode, motivated trainers face confusion and fragmentation because the institutional environment offers no receiving structure for what they have learned.

  + context: Conventional programme evaluation treats success and failure as properties of the training; this pattern reframes them as properties of the institutional architecture.
  + if: You want to explain why the same training produces divergent outcomes across institutions.
  + however: The modes are not permanent features of institutions; they describe a relationship between input and architecture that can shift if architectural conditions change.
  + then: Diagnose the implementation mode at each institution before attributing success or failure to the training itself. Invest in architectural conditions (workload models, managerial backing, feedback systems, co-ownership pathways) rather than solely in better inputs.
  + because: When motivated, capable trainers fail to sustain delivery, the cause is almost never motivational or cognitive — it is architectural. Reframing the problem redirects intervention design from "better training" to "better receiving conditions."
      + mechanism: Institutional architecture acts as a multiplier, absorber, or deflector of training inputs depending on the presence of workload allocation, feedback infrastructure, and co-ownership pathways.
      + counterfactual: If we treat failure as a training problem and respond with better inputs into the same architecture, we repeat the cycle.
      + applies-when: A programme operates across institutions with varying infrastructure and observes divergent outcomes from similar inputs.
      + does-not-apply: A programme with direct control over institutional conditions at all delivery sites.
      + signals: Same training, different outcomes; motivation high but delivery fragile or absent; trainers describe institutional barriers rather than content gaps.
      + evidence: Qualitative implementation modes across four focus groups; COM-B motivation items consistently high (M>5.0) while institutional items consistently low (M<3.8); trainers in failure mode report "I struggled to fit everything together" (T2A) despite high engagement.
  + next-steps:
      - Classify participating institutions by implementation mode.
      - Design differentiated support: architectural investment for mismatch sites, maintenance support for absorbed sites, peer learning from multiplied sites.
      - Track mode transitions over time as architectural conditions change.
  + governance:
      - practice: include implementation mode assessment in annual programme review.
      - metric: proportion of institutions in each mode; mode transitions year-on-year.
